# Dispatcher list - FreeSWITCH backends
# Format: setid  destination  flags  priority  attrs
#
# Flags:
#   0 - No flags (use default)
#   1 - Inactive (destination is down)
#   2 - Probing (being tested)
#   4 - Disable DNS SRV lookups
#   8 - Disable DNS A lookups
#   16 - Delete entry on expire
#
# Priority: Lower = higher priority (0-255)
#
# Attrs: Key-value pairs for custom routing
#   weight=N - Relative weight for weighted distribution
#   maxload=N - Max concurrent calls (for call-load algorithm)
#   socket=udp:IP:PORT - Force specific local socket
#   duid=STRING - Unique destination ID
#
# Load balancing algorithms (used in ds_select_dst):
#   0 - Hash over Call-ID
#   1 - Hash over From URI
#   2 - Hash over To URI
#   3 - Hash over Request-URI
#   4 - Round-Robin
#   5 - Hash over authorization username
#   6 - Random
#   7 - Hash over PV
#   8 - Priority-based selection (use priority field)
#   9 - Weight-based (use weight attr)
#   10 - Call-load distribution (use maxload attr)
#   11 - Relative weight (percentage)
#   12 - Parallel forking to all

# ============================================================
# Group 1: Primary FreeSWITCH Media Servers
# ============================================================
# These handle all call processing - RCF, API Calling, SIP Trunk

# Primary FreeSWITCH instance (host networking)
# Weight: 100, MaxLoad: 2000 concurrent calls
# FS binds to the VM's internal VPC IP (local_ip_v4 = 10.142.0.100)
# so dispatcher must target that IP, not 127.0.0.1
1 sip:10.142.0.100:5080 0 0 weight=100;maxload=2000;duid=fs-primary

# Add additional FreeSWITCH instances here for horizontal scaling:
# 1 sip:freeswitch-2:5080 0 0 weight=100;maxload=2000;duid=fs-secondary
# 1 sip:freeswitch-3:5080 0 0 weight=100;maxload=2000;duid=fs-tertiary

# ============================================================
# Group 2: Bandwidth Standard Carrier (Dallas)
# ============================================================
# Bandwidth Dallas signaling IP for standard/backup trunks.
# Mapped from X-Carrier: standard | backup in route[TO_CARRIER].
#
# PURPOSE: Dispatcher sends periodic SIP OPTIONS to this IP
# (controlled by ds_ping_interval). This serves two functions:
#   1. NAT keepalive — Keeps the SIP signaling NAT pinhole open
#      through GCE's 30-second UDP idle timeout. Without periodic
#      SIP traffic, the NAT mapping expires and inbound SIP from
#      Bandwidth (new INVITEs, re-INVITEs) may not reach Kamailio.
#   2. Health monitoring — Detects carrier unreachability early.
#      If Bandwidth stops responding to OPTIONS, ds_probing marks
#      the destination inactive and logs a warning.
#
# NOTE: This group is for probing/keepalive ONLY. Actual outbound
# call routing to Bandwidth is handled by route[TO_CARRIER] using
# $rd/$du directly — NOT via ds_select_dst on this group.
2 sip:67.231.2.12:5060 0 0 weight=100;duid=bw-dallas-standard

# ============================================================
# Group 3: Bandwidth Premium Carrier (Los Angeles)
# ============================================================
# Bandwidth LA signaling IP for premium/high-CPS trunk.
# Mapped from X-Carrier: premium in route[TO_CARRIER].
# Same keepalive/health-monitoring purpose as Group 2.
3 sip:216.82.238.134:5060 0 0 weight=100;duid=bw-la-premium

# ============================================================
# Notes:
# ============================================================
# - Kamailio will probe each destination every ds_ping_interval seconds
# - Destinations that fail ds_probing_threshold probes are marked inactive
# - Inactive destinations are retried and reactivated after ds_inactive_threshold successes
# - Use ds_mark_dst("p") to manually mark a destination for probing
# - Use ds_mark_dst("i") to manually mark a destination as inactive
# - Use ds_mark_dst("a") to manually mark a destination as active
#
# To reload dispatcher list without restart:
#   kamcmd dispatcher.reload
#
# To view dispatcher status:
#   kamcmd dispatcher.list
